# Basic Git Workflow

The standard Git workflow follows four steps.

```
Modify Files
      │
      ▼
git add
      │
      ▼
git commit
      │
      ▼
git push
```

### Step 1 – Modify Files
Edit source code, HTML, CSS, Python, SQL or other project files.

### Step 2 – git add
Stages the modified files ready to be included in the next commit.

```
git add .
```
The period (`.`) stages all modified files within the project.

### Step 3 – git commit
Creates a permanent snapshot of the project.

```
git commit -m "Completed Browse Collection page"
```

A meaningful commit message should describe what was completed.

### Step 4 – git push
Uploads local commits to a remote Git repository (for example GitHub).

```
git push
```

