# Common Git Commands

## Initialise a Repository
Creates a new Git repository inside the current folder.

```
git init
```

---

## Check Repository Status
Displays modified, staged and untracked files.

```
git status
```

This is one of the most frequently used Git commands.

---

## Stage All Files
Adds all modified files to the staging area.

```
git add .
```

---

## Commit Changes
Creates a snapshot of the current project.

```
git commit -m "Describe completed work"
```

---

## View Commit History
Displays previous commits.

```
git log --oneline
```

---

## Upload to GitHub
Pushes local commits to the remote repository.

```
git push
```

---

# Important Git Concepts

## Repository
A repository (repo) is the complete project being tracked by Git.

The hidden `.git` folder stores all version history.

---

## Working Directory
The current project files being edited.

---

## Staging Area
Temporary area where files are prepared before creating a commit.

---

## Commit
A permanent snapshot of the project.

Each commit records:

* Modified files
* Date and time
* Commit message
* Unique commit identifier

---

## GitHub
GitHub is an online hosting platform for Git repositories.

Git stores version history locally.

GitHub stores copies online for backup and collaboration.

